{{Infobox organization | name = Abisko Scientific Research Station | native_name = | image = ANS winter.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = ANS in the winter | predecessor = Vassijaure naturvetenskapliga station | formation = {{start date and age|1903 }} | location = [[Abisko]] | region = [[Norrbotten]], [[Arctic]] | language = [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[English language|English]] | leader_title = Head of Department of Terrestrial Research | leader_name = Magnus Augner | parent_organization = [[Swedish Polar Research Secretariat]] | affiliations = [[University of the Arctic]] | staff = 12 | website = {{URL|polar.se/en/abisko-naturvetenskapliga-station/}}
}}
The '''Abisko Scientific Research Station''' ('''ANS''') is a field [[research station]] managed by the [[Swedish Polar Research Secretariat]]. Situated on the south shore of Lake [[Torneträsk]], it lies at the edge of the [[Abisko National Park]]. The station conducts ecological, geological, geomorphological and meteorological research in subarctic environments and each year about 500 scientists visit from all over the world. The varied geological, topographical and climatic conditions of the area allow it to be inhabited by a range of [[flora]] and [[fauna]]. These features, which have caused the area to be given [[National Park]] status, also make it an important place for scientific research, particularly of [[:wikt:alpine|alpine]] and [[subalpine]] [[ecosystems]].
==The station== The first proper field station to be established in the area dates back to 1903, however the official station has only been affiliated with the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences]] since 1935. The station holds meteorological datasets extending back to 1913, including air and soil temperature, precipitation and UV radiation. The research station has been the site of many long-term experiments investigating climate change impacts <ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Jonasson | first1 = C. | last2 = Sonesson | first2 = M. | last3 = Christensen | first3 = T. R. | last4 = Callaghan | first4 = T. V.|author-link4=Terry Callaghan | title = Environmental Monitoring and Research in the Abisko Area—An Overview | doi = 10.1007/s13280-012-0301-6 | journal = [[AMBIO]] | volume = 41 | issue = Suppl 3 | pages = 178–186 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22864692| pmc =3535060 }}</ref> and is part of the [[International Tundra Experiment]] (ITEX) which is an international collaboration investigating the effects of environmental change on plants in circumpolar ecosystems. Since December 2010 the station is managed by the [[Swedish Polar Research Secretariat]].
The research station today consists of [[laboratories]] and general workrooms containing a variety of scientific equipment, and also of various 'outposts' where research is carried out ''in situ''. It is used for research, teaching and meetings, and has a large collection of scientific books and papers available on site.
==Current research== [[File:methanestorflaket.JPG|right|thumb|[[Poly(methyl methacrylate)|PMMA]] chambers used to measure [[methane]] and [[CO2|CO<sub>2</sub>]] emissions in [[Storflaket]] [[peat]] [[bog]] near [[Abisko]].]] Though many research projects are carried out at the station regarding [[geography]] and [[biology]] in general, particular emphasis is placed on [[meteorology]] and [[plant ecology]]. Many of these projects overlap as the station hosts research into [[climate change]] in the region and the resulting changes to plant communities. In recent years, research has included work on permafrost degradation,<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Åkerman | first1 = H. J. | last2 = Johansson | first2 = M. | doi = 10.1002/ppp.626 | title = Thawing permafrost and thicker active layers in sub-arctic Sweden | journal = [[Permafrost and Periglacial Processes]] | volume = 19 | issue = 3 | pages = 279 | year = 2008 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> the importance of winter climate change <ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bokhorst | first1 = S. | last2 = Bjerke | first2 = J. W. | last3 = Tømmervik | first3 = H. | last4 = Preece | first4 = C. | last5 = Phoenix | first5 = G. K. | title = Ecosystem Response to Climatic Change: The Importance of the Cold Season | doi = 10.1007/s13280-012-0310-5 | journal = [[AMBIO]] | volume = 41 | issue = Suppl 3 | pages = 246–255 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22864698| pmc =3535051 }}</ref> and tree-line dynamics.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Rundqvist | first1 = S. | last2 = Hedenås | first2 = H. | last3 = Sandström | first3 = A. | last4 = Emanuelsson | first4 = U. | last5 = Eriksson | first5 = H. K. | last6 = Jonasson | first6 = C. | last7 = Callaghan | first7 = T. V.|author-link7=Terry Callaghan | doi = 10.1007/s13280-011-0174-0 | title = Tree and Shrub Expansion over the Past 34 Years at the Tree-Line Near Abisko, Sweden | journal = [[AMBIO]] | volume = 40 | issue = 6 | pages = 683–692 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21954730| pmc =3357856 }}</ref>
Abisko Scientific Research Station is a member of the international network [[University of the Arctic]].
