{{Infobox protected area | name = Antelope Range and Livestock Research Station | alt_name = | iucn_category = | photo = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | photo_width = | map = South Dakota | map_alt = | map_caption = | map_width = | relief = | label = | label_position = | mark = | marker_size = | location = | nearest_city = [[Reva, South Dakota]] | coordinates = {{coords|45.5041008|N|103.281593|W|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|8300|acres}} | designation = | authorized = | created = | established = | designated = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_ref = | governing_body = | administrator = | operator = [[South Dakota State University]] | owner = | world_heritage_site = | website = | url = {{url|http://www3.sdstate.edu/aes/stations/antelope/index.cfm}} | child = | embedded = }}
The '''Antelope Range and Livestock Research Station''' is operated by [[South Dakota State University]] and its extension programs to improve [[ranch|ranching]] in [[South Dakota]]. The site is {{convert|8300|acres}} large, the largest of SDSU’s research stations. This land was owned by the state and operated as an [[Pronghorn|pronghorn antelope]] preserve until 1947, when it was transferred to the agricultural university for [[Agricultural science|research]] into "the balance between cattle and [[Sheep farming|sheep]] production and protection and renewal of range resources". Current work focuses on sustainable [[Beef cattle|beef]] and sheep production on [[rangeland]]. There are 120 head of beef cow and 400 sheep now on the range.<ref name=reeis>{{cite web|url=http://www.reeis.usda.gov/web/crisprojectpages/0028154-antelope-range.html|title=Antelope Range Field Station|website=[[USDA]] Research, Education, and Economics Information System|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> [[North Dakota State University]] operates a similar research station at [[Hettinger, North Dakota]], which often partners with SDSU's Antelope station for sheep research.<ref name=official>{{cite web|url=http://www3.sdstate.edu/aes/stations/antelope/index.cfm |title=Antelope Range and Livestock Research Station |website=[[South Dakota State University]] |accessdate=27 January 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905171332/http://www.sdstate.edu/aes/stations/antelope/index.cfm |archivedate=5 September 2015 }}</ref>
The land is {{convert|14|miles}} east of [[Buffalo, South Dakota]], south of [[South Dakota Highway 20]].<ref name=fieldday>{{cite news|url=http://rapidcityjournal.com/business/agriculture/antelope-range-livestock-station-field-day-sept/article_9da2030c-1fc5-5d4e-87e7-27317d864f62.html|title=Antelope Range Livestock Station field day Sept. 29|newspaper=[[Rapid City Journal]]|date=17 September 2005|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> It lies in the middle of [[Harding County, South Dakota]], in the far northwest corner of the state. The station is about {{Convert|2|miles}} west of [[Custer National Forest]].
==See also== Antelope Range and Livestock Research Station is one of seven South Dakota State University field stations.<ref name=official /> The others are: * [[Cottonwood Range and Livestock Field Station]] near [[Philip, South Dakota|Philip]], for cow/calf and [[Cow|heifer]] management, as well as water quality issues * [[Oak Lake Field Station]] near [[White, South Dakota|White]], for [[biofuel]]s, [[prairie]] biodiversity, [[fire ecology]], and [[stream]] ecology * [[Dakota Lakes Research Station]] near [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]], for study of [[irrigation]] and drylands * [[Northeast Research Station]] near [[South Shore, South Dakota|South Shore]], for herbicides, fertilizers, and [[agronomics]] * [[Southeast Experiment Station]] near [[Beresford, South Dakota|Beresford]], for crops and small grains * [[West River Ag Center]] near [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]], for outreach in [[West River, South Dakota|West River]]
==External links== * {{official| http://www3.sdstate.edu/aes/stations/antelope/index.cfm}}
