{{short description|A terrane that includes parts of Alaska, Siberia and the continental shelf between them}} {{multiple image | total_width = 600 | perrow = 2 | image1 = Arctic Alaska-Chukotka 150Ma.jpg | image2 = Arctic Alaska-Chukotka 100Ma.jpg | image3 = Arctic Alaska-Chukotka 50Ma.jpg | image4 = Arctic Alaska-Chukotka 0Ma.jpg | footer = The Arctic Alaska-Chukotka terrane (in blue) at 150, 100, 50, and 0&nbsp;Ma. View centered on the North Pole. }} The '''Arctic Alaska-Chukotka terrane''' ('''AAC''') is a [[microcontinent]] that today encompasses the [[Alaska North Slope|North Slope]], [[Brooks Range]], and [[Seward Peninsula]] of northern Alaska; the [[Chukotka Peninsula]], [[New Siberia Islands]], and [[Wrangel Island]] in eastern Siberia; and the continental shelves of the [[Bering Sea|Bering]], [[Beaufort Sea|Beaufort]], and [[Chukchi Sea|Chukchi]] seas.<ref name="Strauss-etal">{{Harvnb|Strauss|Hoiland|Ward|Johnson|2017|loc=Introduction, pp. 649–652}}</ref> Comparable in size to Greenland, the AAC is the largest of the Neoproterozoic–Early Paleozoic continental fragments now dispersed around the Arctic Ocean; some of which possibly formed the continent [[Arctida]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Till|2016|loc=Arctic Alaska–Chukotka Microplate, p. 220}}</ref>
The AAC originated on the shores of the [[Iapetus Ocean]] and is a composite [[terrane]] made of fragments from the [[Baltica]], [[Laurentia]], and [[Siberia (continent)|Siberia]] continents, as well as the ocean floor of the [[Panthalassa|Panthalassic ocean]]. The AAC has a complex geological history that includes the [[Grenville Orogeny|Grenville]], [[Timanide Orogen|Timanian]], [[Caledonian Orogeny|Caledonian]]–[[Alleghanian orogeny|Appalachian]], and [[Ellesmere Island|Ellesmerian]] [[Orogeny|orogenies]].<ref name="Strauss-etal" />
The Proterozoic–Carboniferous histories of Arctic Alaska and Chukotka are similar but their Triassic–Jurassic histories are apparently distinct. Whether or not they were separate blocks before the Mesozoic opening of the [[Amerasia Basin]] is disputed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Till|2016|loc=Arctic Alaska and Chukotka—One Microplate or Two?, pp. 232–233}}</ref> The age of the [[Basement (geology)|basement]] of the AAC remains enigmatic, hence also details about the microcontinent's ancient, tectonic history. It is, nevertheless, clear from Neoproterozoic igneous rocks that the AAC was not originally part of Laurentia, but most likely Baltica. The microcontinent was obviously involved in a series of magmatic events, beginning at {{Circa}} 1.6–1.4&nbsp;{{Abbr|Ga|billion years ago}}, and ending in the [[Avalonia]]–[[Cadomian Orogeny|Cadomian]] orogeny.<ref>{{Harvnb|Amato|Aleinikoff|Akinin|McClelland|2014|loc=Abstract}}</ref>
