{{no footnotes|date=February 2013}}
'''Nicolae Frolov''' (1876&ndash;1948) was a [[Romania]]n geologist and agronomist from [[Bessarabia]]. He was noted for his work in explicating the hydrology of Bessarabia and as director of the Chișinău National Museum.

Born in [[Corneşti, Ungheni|Corneşti]], [[Raionul Ungheni|Ungheni]], Bessarabia, he graduated from Chișinău Theological Seminary and then went to Estonia where in 1904 he graduated from the [[University of Tartu|University of Dorpat]] (now Tartu). After which he taught at the universities of [[Saint Petersburg State University|St, Petersburg]], [[Kiev University|Kiev]] and [[Odessa University|Odessa]].  In 1921, he moved to [[Chişinău]] and was appointed as director of the Chișinău Museum. He taught agronmy and agricultural economics at the university there until 1940, when he retired and moved to Romania.  He died in [[Iaşi]].

