{{italic title}}
'''''The Sibling Society''''' is a book by poet, activist and author [[Robert Bly]], published in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher=WorldCat |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/sibling-society/oclc/33667615 |title=The sibling society (book, 1996) |accessdate=19 January 2011 }}</ref> Bly argues that modern men face difficulties caused by an inability to reach full maturity,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06EED91439F93AA25755C0A960958260 |newspaper=New York Times |first=Walter |last=Goodman |title=BOOKS OF THE TIMES; Fe, Fi, Fo, Whoa! The Inner Giant Has Taken Over. |date=19 June 1996}}</ref> and discusses the consequences this has for the societies in which they live.<ref>{{cite web | title = Just Grow Up! :  THE SIBLING SOCIETY. By Robert Bly | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-15/books/bk-43980_1_robert-bly 
|date=September 15, 1996| accessdate = 2014-03-15 | publisher = LA Times}}</ref>  The core of Bly's thesis seems derived from Alexander Mitscherlich's 1963 monograph, Society without the Father (Auf dem Weg zur vaterlosen Gesellschaft), for which Bly wrote an introduction to the American edition ({{ISBN|9780060974206}}).

